text: On July 5, 1852, Frederick Douglass stood before an abolitionist group and gave one of his most famous speeches: “What To The Slave Is The Fourth of July?”  That speech confronted the glaring hypocrisy of a day celebrating freedom in a country that still endorsed the bondage and forced labor of more than 1 in 8 of its residents. And while the institution of slavery has been abolished, its consequences have endured through the generations. In July 2020, five young Douglass descendants read and responded to excerpts of that speech. They reflected on America’s ongoing pursuit of liberty and justice for all. This project was inspired by the documentary project Whitman, Alabama 🎞️ and 💬 by NPR

text: Today’s reminder: American Sign Language (ASL) and English are different languages! 🎞️ by @leila  TRANSCRIPT: Let’s talk about Musk’s tweet. Or xeet. Whatever you call it. ”What’s the point of sign language in a video if you already have subtitles?” This was newsworthy because of who Elon Musk is and his position, power, and influence. But the reality is, many hearing people have the same thought. That was the most common question I got after I did “Barbie With ASL”. This has already been said multiple times, but I’m going to repeat it for emphasis. ASL and English are two different languages. Imagine trying to understand the news or a movie in a second language. Is that truly accessible? And if you don’t know a second language, then you’ve likely had information catered to your first language your entire life. That in itself is a privilege, my friend. If you have any knowledge of the Deaf community, you probably know that language deprivation seriously impacts our community. Many deaf people struggle with English for reasons that I can’t fit in this reel, but the short answer is: Because of audism. As a Deaf person, sign language is much more natural for me than spoken or written language. I process information more naturally through a visual language. The bottom line is, true accessibility means getting information in my language. And ASL is my language.
